<TITLE> 'State-of-the-art' Jamarat Bridge to receive 3 million pilgrims </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MUZDALIFA, Saudi Arabia, Nov 27 (bdnews24.com) - Saudi Arabia's newly completed five-storey hi-tech Jamarat Bridge is expected to ensure a smooth flow of nearly three million hajj pilgrims during the devil stoning ritual this year to prevent any repeat of past tragedies due to crowd disasters. Millions of Muslims headed to Muzdalifa on Thursday, after spending the day on the plain of Arafat, to cast stones at the devil in the most dangerous part of the annual hajj pilgrimage. The new "state-of-the-art" Jamarat Bridge is designed to accommodate up to five million pilgrims, say Saudi authorities. The hi-tech bridge has 10 entrances and 12 exits over its four levels to allow the flow of 300,000 pilgrims per hour. It is also equipped with the most up-to-date technology to help authorities intervene in case of any deadly stampedes. Pilgrims will not be allowed to carry large bags during the ritual, say officials who will monitor and control the flow of pilgrims. At Muzdalifa, the pilgrims collect pebbles to throw at walls at the Jamarat Bridge on three occasions over the next three days in an act that symbolises the rejection of the devil's temptations. The faithful must hurl seven pebbles from behind a fence or from the overhead bridge at each of the three 18-meter high concrete pillars on the spot where the devil appeared to Prophet Abraham. The bridge has been the scene of a number of deadly stampedes; 362 people were crushed to death there in 2006 in the worst hajj tragedy since 1
